> Good work~ Since there are some historical reason and more scenarios, I would like to offer more information.
> 
> First, there are two bug scenarios:
> 
> (1)
> insert into root.turbine1.d1(timestamp,s1,s2) values(1,1.1,2.2);
> delete timeseries root.turbine1.d1.s1
> create timeseries root.turbine1.d1.s1 with datatype=INT32, encoding=RLE, compression=SNAPPY
> restart IoTDB
> select * from root
> 
> The InsertRowPlan that deserialized from WAL should set isNeedInserfType as false. We only inferTyp when users pass a String value, the WAL already serializes the real data type, so no need to infer type. So, we need to markFailedMeasurementInsertion manually for insertRowPlan.
> 
> (2)
> insert into root.turbine1.d1(timestamp,s1,s2) values(1,1.1,2.2);
> delete timeseries root.turbine1.d1.s1
> restart IoTDB
> select * from root
> 
> This will throw a metadata exception when querying the schema of the InsertPlan, because a measurement is deleted in MManager.
> 
> One way to fix this is to add a parameter of IoTDB.metaManager.getSchemas() indicating that it should return a MeasurementSchema[] with some nulls instead of throw exception when recovering wal.
> 
> Finally, it's better to recover the two cases by an IT. There is an IoTDBRestartIT class, you could use EnvironmentUtils.restartDaemon() to simulate the restart of IoTDB and verify the bugs.

